commitResults.messageTitle: Skeletal version of Duke: greets user, echo user commands, exit if user types "bye"
Added 2 new features: Add user commands to history and List out history of user commands
Added new class Task. Added new feature Mark as Done
Added 3 children class of Task: Todo, Event, Deadline. Refactored function processUserCommand
Fixed bug where there is extra spacing when displaying event and deadline. Added testcases to semi-automate testing of Duke
Added custom Exception: DukeException. Invalid user inputs throws DukeExceptions. Updated testcases for exceptions
Duke.java: Added function deleteTask, renamed function addToList to addTasks EXPECTED.TXT, input.txt: updated testcases for deleteTask
Update EXPECTED.TXT runtest.sh: pause results window before closing
Update Duke.java to follow Java coding standards
Extract Duke methods into OOP style
commitResults.messageBody:
Duke.java contains main code features.

When more features are added, Duke.java becomes cluttered. This reduces
readability.

Methods are extracted into various java files (AddCommand... etc)

This reduces code length in Duke.java, and methods are allocated
appropriately in their respective new classes.

TaskList is always generated from scratch.

This does not allow retention of tasks created before.

Creating Storage saves the TaskList and allows loading when Duke is run
subsequently.

Deadline stores date as String.

Storing date as LocalDate object is more meaningful. It gives access to
methods that deal with dates, such as comparing which date comes first.

commitResults.messageBody:
Current Duke has no test automation. As program grows, it will become
harder to spot bugs.

Use Gradle and junit to help automate building and testing.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update code to meet coding standards

commitResults.messageBody:
User stores tasks in taskList but can only choose to access all tasks.

This is not user-friendly. User might just want to look for relevant
tasks in the whole list.

User can now find tasks in taskList using command "find" followed by
a keyword to filter tasks containing that keyword.
